  "27": {
    "inputs": {
      "value": "Extreme macro side-on close-up of a single dragonfly resting on a dried reed stem at dawn, focused tightly on its outstretched, translucent wing. The wing is a delicate lattice of fine black veins dividing the membrane into hundreds of tiny irregular cells, each pane catching the low sun and flashing with faint iridescent rainbow sheens of blue, green, and amber. A scattering of dew clings to the leading edge of the wing and along the reed, each droplet glowing. The dragonfly's segmented body is partly visible and softly out of focus at the left edge of the frame, its large compound eye a blur of metallic teal. Strong warm backlighting from a low golden-hour sun behind the insect makes the wing membrane glow like stained glass, rim-lighting the veins and igniting the dew into points of light, while the front of the wing falls into cool shadow. Background is a deep, smooth wash of out-of-focus dawn blue and gold. Shot on a 180mm macro lens, f/5.6, ISO 200, focus-stacked for crisp veins, natural backlight. Rendered with the warm tonality and fine grain of Kodak Portra 400 — soft highlights, gentle contrast, organic color. Luminous, intricate, serene fine-art macro photography."
    },
